Our new community read aloud book, The Lemonade War, was distributed to the youngest member of K-5 families over the last two weeks. If your family did not receive a copy, please pick one up in the main office or contact stephanie.saggione@laaa.k12.de.us. The book is available in both English and Spanish!

We recommend starting the story tonight, September 1st, by listening to someone in your family read aloud Chapter 1. Continue reading a chapter every night to get through the book this month. We invite you to watch Facebook for posts about activities you can try together. Follow the daily trivia questions on the libraryâ€™s Remind messages or on Instagram @mrs.saggione. If you aren't signed up for the library remind account, please email Mrs. Saggione for the code or send a private message here so we can provide it. Thank you and Happy Reading! ğŸ“–ğŸ‹

Yesterday was the commemoration of the 57th Anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr.'s I Have A Dream Speach and the March on Washington. Tens of thousands of attendees gathered in Washington DC as a commitment to ending police violence, dismantling systemic racism, and ensuring access to vote. ASPIRA is committed to helping achieve racial and social justice and will be sharing opportunities of ways you can partner to help us soon. Please see the following video created by members of our Operation Justice team!

https://youtu.be/2euBtaYFg-8

United Way of Delaware and YWCA of Delaware have partnered to provide awesome resources. Their 21-Day Racial Equity Challenge provides participants with daily emails with suggestions on articles to read, videos to view, and thoughts to consider. All the activities are designed to increase your readiness to help dismantle systemic racism in Delaware. ASPIRA has accepted the challenge and we would love for you to join us! Though the activities have already started, you can read up on previous days as well. To learn more or to sign up, click here!

https://deracialequitychallenge.org/

For our 6th grade Civil Rights unit, students learned about different past and modern protests/marches/boycotts. They compared the similarities and differences of one past and one modern march. post_text: LAAA welcomes three teachers from Saudi Arabia as part of a professional development program through the University of Delaware; Ahmed Alatawi, Sultan Alghamdi, and Omar Dahaba. The mission of the Khbrat program, which translates into English as "experiences,â€ is to develop professional and academic language skills in Delaware schools, which can be transferred to Saudi Arabia. At the completion of the Khbrat program, Ahmed, Sultan, and Omar will return to Saudi Arabia to share their experiences and knowledge with their colleagues to empower them to lead discussions within the Saudi Arabian educational system. There are a total of 40 teachers in the University of DelawareKhbrat program, and more than 1000 teachers in other states and countries looking to achieve the same goal.
